register.description: Hardware Event External Multiplex Control Register

bitfield.description: Specifies the value that the optional external multiplexing logic uses to select the hardware events to connect to the STM. The value of this register is output from the STM on the HEEXTMUX[7:0] signals. The behavior of the multiplexing logic is IMPLEMENTATION DEFINED. This field is reset to zero.
The STPv2 master number for the hardware event trace: 0x80 Hardware events are associated with master ID 0x80.
The size of the STMHEEXTMUXR.EXTMUX bit field: 0b011 8 bits wide.
The number of hardware events supported by the STM: 0b001000000 64 hardware events.
Data compression on hardware event tracing support: 0b11 Programmable data compression support. The STM implements the STMHEMCR.COMPEN bit.
Specifies the STMHEMASTR support: 0b0 The STMHEMASTR is read-only.
Hardware event error detection support: 0b1 Implemented. The STM implements the STMHEMCR.ERRDETECT bit.
Identifies vendor-specific modifications or mappings: 0b0000 Vendor-specific information.
Identifies the revision of the programmers model: 0b0001 Revision.
Identifies the programmers model: 0b0001 Hardware event control.

Indicates whether the STM is busy, for example the STM trace FIFO is not empty: 0b0 Not busy. 0b1 Busy.
ATB trace ID. Setting this value to all zeroes or to a value greater than 0x6F might result in UNPREDICTABLE tracing. Reset value of this bit field is UNKNOWN.
Compression enable for stimulus ports: 0b0 Disabled, the STM transmits data transfers based on the size of the transaction. 0b1 Enabled, the STM compresses data transfers to save bandwidth.
The STM implements the STMSYNCR, so this bit is Read As One. 0b1 The STM implements the STMSYNCR.

Determines whether to ignore timestamp requests: 0b0 Disable timestamping. The STM ignores requests for timestamp generation, and treats stimulus port writes that select timestamping as if timestamping were not selected. 0b1 Enable timestamping. If stimulus writes select timestamping, the STM outputs a timestamp according to STPv2.

Low-power interface override when hardware event tracing is enabled: 0b0 The STM can accept a quiescence request on the STM low-power interface when the STMHEMCR.EN bit is set to 0b1. 0b1 If the STMHEMCR.EN bit is set to 0b1, all quiescence requests on the STM low-power interface are denied. Reset value is 0b0.

Controls arbitration between the AXI interface and the hardware event observation interface during flush: 0b0 Priority inversion. When the AXI flush completes, the hardware event observation interface gets priority until the hardware event observation interface flush completes. 0b1 Priority inversion disabled. The AXI always has priority over the hardware event observation interface. Reset value is 0b0.
ASYNC priority: 0b0 Always lower than trace. 0b1 Escalates on second synchronization request. Reset value is 0b0.
Auto-flush: 0b0 Disabled. 0b1 Enabled. The STM automatically drains all data even if the ATB interface is not fully utilized. Reset value is 0b0.
Specifies the STMTCSR.SWOEN bit support: 0b01 Not implemented.
Specifies the STMTCSR.SYNCEN bit support: 0b10 Implemented but always reads as 0b1.
Specifies the STMTCSR.HWTEN bit support: 0b01 Not implemented.
Trigger control support: 0b10 Multi-shot and single-shot triggers supported, the STM implements the STMTRIGCSR.
Trace bus support: 0b0001 CoreSight ATB plus ATB trigger support implemented, the STM implements the STMTCSR.TRACEID and STMTRIGCSR.ATBTRIGEN bit fields.
Specifies the STMSYNCR support: 0b11 Implemented with MODE control.
Specifies the STMTSSTIMR support: 0b1 The STM implements the STMTSSTIMR.FORCETS bit.
Timestamp frequency indication configuration: 0b1 The STMTSFREQR is read-write.
Stimulus port type support: 0b01 Only extended stimulus ports.
Stimulus port transaction type support: 0b10 Both invariant timing and guaranteed transactions.
Specifies the STMPRIVMASKR support: 0b01 Not implemented.
Specifies the STMSPOVERRIDER support: 0b1 STMSPOVERRIDER and STMSPMOVERRIDER implemented.
Data compression on stimulus ports support: 0b11 Data compression support is programmable, the STM implements the STMTCSR.COMPEN bit.
The number of stimulus port masters implemented minus 1: 0b1111111 128 ports.

Sets the value of the ATDATAM[31] output signal: 0b1 Drive logic 0b1. 0b0 Drive logic 0b0.
Sets the value of the ATDATAM[23] output signal: 0b1 Drive logic 0b1. 0b0 Drive logic 0b0.

Sets the value of the ATDATAM[0] output signal: 0b1 Drive logic 0b1. 0b0 Drive logic 0b0.

Ignores writes when the PADDRDBG31 signal is HIGH. When the PADDRDBG31 signal is LOW, a write of 0xC5ACCE55 unlocks the lock control mechanism, enabling further writes with the PADDRDBG31 signal LOW. Other values lock the lock control mechanism, preventing further writes with the PADDRDBG31 signal LOW, except to the STMLAR.
Indicates whether the component implements the STMLAR as 8 bit or 32 bit. 0b0 32 bit.

Returns the current status of the lock. 0b0 Enables write access to the STM. For read accesses to the STMLSR when the PADDRDBG31 signal is HIGH, this bit is always 0b0. 0b1 Blocks write access to the STM. The STM ignores all write accesses to the registers when the PADDRDBG31 signal is LOW. Reads are permitted

Indicates that a lock control mechanism exists for the device. 0b0 No lock control mechanism exists. The STM ignores writes to the STMLAR. For read accesses to the STMLSR when the PADDRDBG31 signal is HIGH, this bit is always 0b0. 0b1 Lock control mechanism is present. For read accesses to the STMLSR when the PADDRDBG31 signal is LOW, this bit is always 0b1.
Indicates the security level for Secure non-invasive debug: 0b10 Disabled. 0b11 Enabled.
Indicates the security level for Secure invasive debug: 0b10 Disabled. 0b11 Enabled.
Indicates the security level for Non-secure non-invasive debug: 0b10 Disabled. 0b11 Enabled.
Indicates the security level for Non-secure invasive debug: 0b10 Disabled. 0b11 Enabled.

Defines the architect of the component: Bits[31:28] Indicates the JEP106 continuation code. Bits[27:21] Indicates the JEP106 identification code. See the Standard Manufacturer’s Identification Code for information about JEP106. For the STM-500, ARM is the architect, and this 11-bit field returns 0x23B.
Indicates the presence of the STMDEVARCH register: 0b1 The STMDEVARCH register is present.
Architecture revision. Returns the revision of the architecture that the ARCHID field specifies. For the STM, this value is 0x1, indicating the STMv1.1 architecture.
Architecture ID. Returns a value that identifies the architecture of the component. For the STM, this value is 0x0A63, indicating the STMv1.1 architecture.
Indicates the number of stimulus ports implemented. 0x10000 65536
Sub-classification within the major category: 0b0110 The component generates trace based on software and hardware stimulus
Major classification grouping for the debug or trace component: 0b0011 The component is a trace source.

This 4-bit value indicates the total contiguous size of the memory window used by the component in powers of two from the standard 4KB. If a component only requires the standard 4KB, this bit field must read as 0x0, 4KB only. For 8KB set to 0x1, for 16KB set to 0x2, for 32KB set to 0x3, and so on. 0x0 The device only occupies 4KB of memory.
JEDEC continuation code indicating the designer of the component, together with the identity code. 0x4 ARM JEDEC identity code is on the fifth bank.
Bits [7:0] of the component part number, specified by the designer of the component. 0b01100011 Lowest eight bits of the part number, 0x963.
Bits [3:0] of the JEDEC identity code indicating the designer of the component, together with the continuation code. 0b1011 Lowest four bits of the JEP106 identity code.
Bits [11:8] of the component part number, specified by the designer of the component. 0b1001 Upper four bits of the part number, 0x963.

An incremental value starting at 0x0 for the first design of this component. The value increases by one for both major and minor revisions and is used as a look-up to establish the exact major and minor revision. 0b0000 The device is at r0p0
Indicates the use of a JEDEC assigned value. This bit is always set. 0b1 The designer ID is specified by JEDEC (http://www.jedec.org).
Bits [6:4] of the JEDEC identity code indicating the designer of the component, together with the continuation code. 0b011 Upper three bits of the JEP106 identity code

Indicates minor errata fixes specific to the design, for example metal fixes after implementation. In most cases this field is zero. ARM recommends that the component designers ensure that the bit field can be changed by a metal fix if required, for example by driving the bit field from registers that reset to zero. 0x0 No metal fixes in the component.
Where the component is reusable IP, this value indicates whether the customer has modified the behavior of the component. In most cases this field is zero. 0x0 No modifications made.
Contains bits [31:21] of the component identification. 0x0D Identification value.
Class of the component, for example, the ROM table or CoreSight component. 0x9 Indicates the component is a CoreSight component.
Contains bits [19:16] of the component identification. 0x0 Identification value.
Contains bits [15:8] of the component identification. 0x05 Identification value.
Contains bits [7:0] of the component identification. 0xB1 Identification value.
